<h1 align=3D"center">High School Algebra Common Core Standards</h1><p align=
=3D"center">Here are the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/links/core-i=
ndex.html">Common Core Standards</a> for High School Algebra, with links to=
 resources that support them. We also encourage plenty of exercises and boo=
k work.</p><div class=3D"corYrSubj">High School Algebra | Seeing Structure =
in Expressions</div>
<div class=3D"corTitle">Interpret the structure of expressions.</div>
<div class=3D"corCore"><span class=3D"corCode">HSA.SSE.A.1</span><span clas=
s=3D"corDescr">Interpret expressions that represent a quantity in terms of =
its context.<br>
a. Interpret parts of an expression, such as terms, factors, and coefficien=
ts.<br>
b. Interpret complicated expressions by viewing one or more of their parts =
as a single entity. For example, interpret P(1+r)^n as the product of P and=
 a factor not depending on P.</span></div><div class=3D"corPages">
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/polyno=
mials.html">Polynomials</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/polyno=
mials-solving.html">Solving Polynomials</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/factor=
ing.html">Factoring in Algebra</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/factor=
ing-quadratics.html">Factoring Quadratics</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/degree=
-expression.html">Degree (of an Expression)</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/polyno=
mials-general-form.html">General Form of a Polynomial</a></div></div>
<div class=3D"corCore"><span class=3D"corCode">HSA.SSE.A.2</span><span clas=
s=3D"corDescr">Use the structure of an expression to identify ways to rewri=
te it. For example, see x^4 - y^4 as (x^2)^2 - (y^2)^2, thus recognizing it=
 as a difference of squares that can be factored as (x^2 - y^2)(x^2 + y^2).=
</span></div><div class=3D"corPages">
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/simpli=
fy.html">Simplify in Algebra</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/factor=
ing.html">Factoring in Algebra</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/factor=
ing-quadratics.html">Factoring Quadratics</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/zero-p=
roduct-property.html">Zero Product Property</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/specia=
l-binomial-products.html">Special Binomial Products</a></div></div>
<div class=3D"corTitle">Write expressions in equivalent forms to solve prob=
lems.</div>
<div class=3D"corCore"><span class=3D"corCode">HSA.SSE.B.3</span><span clas=
s=3D"corDescr">Choose and produce an equivalent form of an expression to re=
veal and explain properties of the quantity represented by the expression.<=
br>
a. Factor a quadratic expression to reveal the zeros of the function it def=
ines.<br>
b. Complete the square in a quadratic expression to reveal the maximum or m=
inimum value of the function it defines.<br>
c. Use the properties of exponents to transform expressions for exponential=
 functions. For example the expression 1,15^t can be rewritten as (1,15^(1/=
12))^(12t) is approximately equal to 1,012^(12t) to reveal the approximate =
equivalent monthly interest rate if the annual rate is 15%.</span></div><di=
v class=3D"corPages">
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/money/compound=
-interest.html">Compound Interest</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/quadra=
tic-equation.html">Quadratic Equations</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/factor=
ing-quadratics.html">Factoring Quadratics</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/comple=
ting-square.html">Completing the Square</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/zero-p=
roduct-property.html">Zero Product Property</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/quadratic-equa=
tion-solver.html">Quadratic Equation Solver</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/quadra=
tic-equation-derivation.html">Derivation of Quadratic Formula</a></div></di=
v>
<div class=3D"corCore"><span class=3D"corCode">HSA.SSE.B.4</span><span clas=
s=3D"corDescr">Derive the formula for the sum of a finite geometric series =
(when the common ratio is not 1), and use the formula to solve problems. Fo=
r example, calculate mortgage payments.</span></div><div class=3D"corPages"=
>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/sequen=
ces-series.html">Sequences</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/partia=
l-sums.html">Partial Sums</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/sigma-=
notation.html">Sigma Notation</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/sequen=
ces-finding-rule.html">Sequences - Finding A Rule</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/sequen=
ces-sums-geometric.html">Geometric Sequences and Sums</a></div></div><div c=
lass=3D"corYrSubj">High School Algebra | Arithmetic with Polynomials &amp; =
Rational Expressions</div>
<div class=3D"corTitle">Perform arithmetic operations on polynomials.</div>
<div class=3D"corCore"><span class=3D"corCode">HSA.APR.A.1</span><span clas=
s=3D"corDescr">Understand that polynomials form a system analogous to the i=
ntegers, namely, they are closed under the operations of addition, subtract=
ion, and multiplication; add, subtract, and multiply polynomials.</span></d=
iv><div class=3D"corPages">
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/sets/closure.h=
tml">Closure</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/like-t=
erms.html">Like Terms</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/polyno=
mials.html">Polynomials</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/polyno=
mials-multiplying.html">Multiplying Polynomials</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/polyno=
mials-general-form.html">General Form of a Polynomial</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/polyno=
mials-multiplication-long.html">Polynomials - Long Multiplication</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/polyno=
mials-adding-subtracting.html">Adding and Subtracting Polynomials</a></div>=
</div>
<div class=3D"corTitle">Understand the relationship between zeros and facto=
rs of polynomials.</div>
<div class=3D"corCore"><span class=3D"corCode">HSA.APR.B.2</span><span clas=
s=3D"corDescr">Know and apply the Remainder Theorem: For a polynomial p(x) =
and a number a, the remainder on division by x - a is p(a), so p(a) =3D 0 i=
f and only if (x - a) is a factor of p(x).</span></div><div class=3D"corPag=
es">
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/polyno=
mials-remainder-factor.html">Remainder Theorem and Factor Theorem</a></div>=
</div>
<div class=3D"corCore"><span class=3D"corCode">HSA.APR.B.3</span><span clas=
s=3D"corDescr">Identify zeros of polynomials when suitable factorizations a=
re available, and use the zeros to construct a rough graph of the function =
defined by the polynomial.</span></div><div class=3D"corPages">
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/simpli=
fy.html">Simplify in Algebra</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/polyno=
mials-solving.html">Solving Polynomials</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/factor=
ing.html">Factoring in Algebra</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/factor=
ing-quadratics.html">Factoring Quadratics</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/polyno=
mials-division-long.html">Polynomials - Long Division</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/polyno=
mials-bounds-zeros.html">Polynomials: Bounds on Zeros</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/polyno=
mials-rule-signs.html">Polynomials: The Rule of Signs</a></div></div>
<div class=3D"corTitle">Use polynomial identities to solve problems.</div>
<div class=3D"corCore"><span class=3D"corCode">HSA.APR.C.4</span><span clas=
s=3D"corDescr">Prove polynomial identities and use them to describe numeric=
al relationships. For example, the polynomial identity (x^2 + y^2)^2 =3D (x=
^2 - y^2)^2 + (2xy)^2 can be used to generate Pythagorean triples.</span></=
div><div class=3D"corPages">
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/pythagorean_tr=
iples.html">Pythagorean Triples</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/polyno=
mials-dividing.html">Dividing Polynomials</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/factor=
ing.html">Factoring in Algebra</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/factor=
ing-quadratics.html">Factoring Quadratics</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/specia=
l-binomial-products.html">Special Binomial Products</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/polyno=
mials-division-long.html">Polynomials - Long Division</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/pythag=
orean-triples.html">Pythagorean Triples - Advanced</a></div></div>
<div class=3D"corCore"><span class=3D"corCode">HSA.APR.C.5</span><span clas=
s=3D"corDescr">Know and apply that the Binomial Theorem for the expansion o=
f (x + y)^n in powers of x and y for a positive integer n, where x and y ar=
e any numbers, with coefficients determined for example by Pascal's Triangl=
e. (The Binomial Theorem can be proved by mathematical induction or by a co=
mbinatorial argument.)</span></div><div class=3D"corPages">
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/binomi=
al-theorem.html">Binomial Theorem</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/activity/subse=
ts.html">Activity: Subsets</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/pascals-triang=
le.html">Pascal's Triangle</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/quincunx-=
explained.html">Quincunx Explained</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/factor=
ial.html">Factorial Function !</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/combinatorics/=
combinations-permutations.html">Combinations and Permutations</a></div>
<div class=3D"corPage"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/combinatorics/=
combinations-permutations-calculator.html">Combinations and Permutations Ca=
